Emptier streets may be encouraging some drivers to flout traffic safety laws, including speed limits.
Despite there being far fewer vehicles on the road due to COVID-19 stay-at-home orders, state highway safety officials across the country are seeing a severe spike in speeding.
This March, the State Patrol issued 103 speeding citations for people going over 100 miles per hour compared to 64 last March.
Troopers say theyâ€™ve clocked more drivers speeding during the pandemic.
CBS reports this is happening all around the country with traffic deaths up in some areas even though traffic on the roads is way down.